<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="37" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,383,927,952]" box="[264,383,927,952]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis box="[264,383,927,952]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1325,996,1265]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
Medium­sized species, wingspan 
<quantity box="[663,794,996,1022]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.15" metricValueMax="2.7" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" unit="mm" value="21.5" valueMax="27.0" valueMin="16.0">16–27 mm</quantity>
. Forewings brown to gray­brown, transverse lines straight, transverse median or transverse posterior line widest, suffused. Male hind tibia swollen, with two hair tufts, without apical spurs; 8 
<superScript attach="left" box="[945,958,1076,1090]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">th</superScript>
sternite wide basally, concave medially, right ceras curved medially, left absent. Sacculus of the male genitalia vestigial; valvula pronounced; vesica with curved cornutus at base. Signum of the female genitalia ovoid, granulate. Montane species in 
<collectingRegion box="[722,783,1199,1225]" country="China" name="Xizang" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Tibet</collectingRegion>
and surrounding areas. Species included: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Oberthur" baseAuthorityYear="1923" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Scopula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dubernardi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">S. dubernardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1919" box="[452,595,1239,1264]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Scopula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="segregata">
<emphasis box="[452,595,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">S. segregata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
